OpenCL and CUDA are two different platforms for designing and implementing parallel algorithms on GPUs.

OpenCL is an open standard, cross-platform programming language for parallel computing, whereas CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) is a proprietary C-based language created by NVIDIA specifically for programming GPUs.

Both have parallel computing capabilities, but OpenCL is more flexible as it can run on different GPUs from different vendors. CUDA can only run on NVIDIA GPUs.

However, CUDA has better hardware and software support compared to OpenCL, making it easier to use for developers.

OpenCL is also more straightforward to use as it integrates with most operating systems, whereas CUDA requires installing additional software on Windows.
